desc: Based on its location in a major urban‐industrial center (Katowice city Silesian Voivodeship) with above‐average economic activity yet not on the same level as a national capital I would classify ulica Tadeusza Kościuszki Brynów-Osiedle Zgrzebnioka in Katowice as: High.

Based on its location in the rural gmina of Ostrów Wielkopolski (Wielkopolskie) – a moderately strong economic region comparable to other medium‐ranked rural areas (e.g. Daninów near Konin) – the most fitting class is:

Answer: Medium

Based on its profile as a predominantly rural county in Wielkopolskie—outside of the major urban centers like Poznań—and by analogy with similarly sized Polish districts whose GDPs fall below €1 billion Kotusz (in Kamieniec commune Grodziski county) would be classified as Low.
Based on Szczecin’s status as a regional capital its sizeable population port facilities and diversified economy its Dąbie district would be classified as High.
Based on its location in Lubiński (a mining‐driven above‐average GDP powiat) – comparable to other medium‐rank Polish districts in your examples – Rynarcice 28 falls into the Medium class.

Based on its location in Trzebnicki (a Wrocław‐adjacent) district of Dolnośląskie – analogous to other counties bordering a regional capital (e.g. Miński Koniński) that we’ve rated “Medium” – the most appropriate GDP class for Wisznia Mała is:

Answer: Medium

Based on Tucholski’s predominantly rural character relatively small population and absence of major industrial or service hubs (unlike nearby Bydgoszcz/Toruń) its per-district GDP would fall into the “Low” class.  
Answer: Low
Based on its being a small village in a predominantly rural gmina in Łódzkie (rather than a heavy‐industry or major suburban district) Opole in Parzęczew (Zgierski) would be classified as Low.

Based on the rural agriculture-dominated character of Wysokomazowiecki County in Podlaskie—one of Poland’s less economically developed voivodeships—and in line with similar assignments for small villages in Łódzkie Lubelskie or Wielkopolskie the most fitting class is:  
Answer: Low

Based on the address (Veľká Maňa is in Nové Zámky District of the Nitra Region) and knowing Nitra’s regional GDP sits at roughly €9–10 billion (placing it between Slovakia’s top‐end “High” regions like Bratislava/Košice and its lower “Low” regions) Nitra should be classed as Medium.  
Answer: Medium

Based on its position among Czech NUTS‐3’s (Ústecký’s GDP is on the order of €9–11 billion well below Prague and South Moravia but above the very smallest regions) it falls into the “Low” category.  
Answer: Low

Based on Fejér’s relatively strong industrial base (notably around Székesfehérvár and the Audi plant) and its above‐national‐average GDP per capita yet still trailing the very top Czech and Hungarian regions (e.g. Budapest or Prague) the appropriate class is:

Answer: Medium
Based on Tolna county’s estimated GDP (roughly €4 bn) and comparing with the benchmarks above (where regions around €3–5 bn classify as Medium) Varsád Tolna falls into the Medium class.

Based on Bács-Kiskun county’s overall economic profile – a mix of agriculture moderate industrial activity (e.g. the Mercedes plant in Kecskemét) and a GDP level below Hungary’s top‐tier regions but above the weakest rural areas – I would classify Tiszakécske (Strand utca Bács-Kiskun) as Medium.
